artist.name: Lady GaGa
artist.blurb: Given that Lady GaGa's style and sounds have dominated the year in pop it may only surprise a few of you that she's stormed to the top of our listener chart. Released in the UK in January (although other territories had it earlier) The Fame has proved to be the most impressive, assured, catchy and triumphant debut album of the year, and possibly for a lot longer than that too. A fully-formed star from the off, Lady GaGa brought electro, hip-hop, pop, dance and a little dash of rock to the party, a lively cocktail that proved tough to shake on radio stations, TV shows, soundtracks... pretty much anywhere with a speaker actually. If The Fame is the album of the year then surely 'Poker Face' is the defining track. While GaGa initially claimed the track was clearly about sex and gambling, the New York native later revealed during a 2am set in Palm Springs that the track related to her experiences as a bisexual. It remains at the top of her artist scrobbles week-in, week-out, often generating as many as double the plays of singles 'LoveGame' and 'Paparazzi', and it has been such a success that Christopher Walken and Eric Cartman have both been moved to cover it. Lady GaGa will be touring The Monster Ball in support of new album The Fame Monster; maybe you'll see her here next year?

artist.name: The Killers
artist.blurb: From a city famed for entertainment, illusion and disappointment The Killers haven't done too badly. The Las Vegas foursome have released three albums since single 'Somebody Told Me' lit up indie clubs back in 2003, have also snuck out a B-sides compilation and, most recently, a live album capturing their Albert Hall residency this summer. Fronted by the charismatic — sometimes confrontational — Brandon Flowers, the band have done more than attract the kind of trendsetters that program TV soundtracks: they've charmed the world. Day & Age was released last November, and while it wasn't an instant critical success fans of the band had the record on heavy rotation for the year. Consistently high scrobbles from more than two million of you (one of two Top 40 bands to reach so many this year) make them a force to be reckoned with, and new material is hotly anticipated. If any tracks prove to be as catchy as 'Human', or as epic as 'Spaceman', then they might just about budge 'Somebody Told Me' and 'Mr Brightside' out of their top tracks. Don't hold your breath though. The Killers will stay on the road in 2010, after playing to some 38,000 of you this year.

artist.name: Lily Allen
artist.blurb: Perhaps the first true MySpace sensation, Lily Allen became a superstar after demos of tracks 'LDN' and 'Smile' first began circulating on her page. Largely unnoticed by her label initially, they were soon bombarded with press requests, which forced them into action. In no time at all she had decamped to a studio with Mark Ronson and Greg Kurstin, and the group set about laying down one of the biggest pop records of the decade. Allen's debut Alright, Still became a multi-platinum success around the world, leaving the star little time to regroup. It's Not Me, It's You dropped in February, and you began to play it in earnest immediately. Allen's album generated almost 2 million more scrobbles than The Prodigy's effort, perhaps in part due to the strength of tracks like twee bounce-along 'Not Fair' and 'Fuck You'. The centrepiece though remains 'The Fear', an honest and open track which echoes through the speaker; a little confession that perhaps she's not quite at home in all this. Of all the top ten she has the highest listener attendance at her live shows, and she's the highest-placed British artist on this year's chart. She will start 2010 on the road.

artist.name: The Prodigy
artist.blurb: Big beat pioneers The Prodigy can boast an almost 20 year career since they emerged from the wilds of Essex in 1990. Since then the band have headlined Glastonbury and Lollapalooza, survived drug addiction and rehab, and continually released commercially successful hard dance music. Despite several thousand fewer of you listening to Invaders Must Die than Tonight: Franz Ferdinand, The Prodigy still nudged past the Glasweigian rockers and into number four. Still best remembered for 'Firestarter' and 'Smack My Bitch Up', both of these tracks have now been pushed to the fringe of the band's chart by Invaders Must Die. The album was a long time coming; it took Liam Howlett several years to regroup after Always Outnumbered, Never Outgunned, and while they had never officially left the band it may have taken some persuading to bring original members Keith Flint and Maxim back into the fold. It resulted in a powerful album, worthy of the band's best; 'Omen', backed with a haunting xylophone loop, stormed through the band's live set while 'Invaders Must Die' boasted the high-pitched production of Best Of 2008 act Does It Offend You, Yeah? The band will be touring long into 2010, including headline events at England's National Bowl.

artist.name: Franz Ferdinand
artist.blurb: Part of the wave of guitar rock to come out of Britain in the early '00s, Franz Ferdinand have been one of the most successful of their contemporaries despite only having released three albums. The band formed in Glasgow, the members linked through previous bands, art school and the famously supportive music scene in Scotland's second city. Debut album Franz Ferdinand was released in 2004, to commercial and critical acclaim, and the band have been busy recording and touring ever since. Reportedly unhappy with second album You Could Have It So Much Better, Tonight: Franz Ferdinand saw the band adopt a more dancefloor friendly sound, with tracks 'Ulysses' and 'No You Girls' returning to the jerky pop of early singles 'Take Me Out' and 'This Fire'. They toured heavily supporting the record, reaching more than 44,000 of you at festivals and gigs this year. They also found time to squeeze in a cover of Britney Spears' 'Womanizer', a song since reputed to be one of their most requested. In the new year Franz Ferdinand will be touring South America, and are likely to return to the festival circuit before recording new material.

artist.name: Beyoncé
artist.blurb: Beyoncé Knowles began her pop career with Destiny's Child in 1997, the group forming around a Texas high school. The all-girl line-up continually shuffled during its ten year career but it was clear from the outset that, of all the members, Beyoncé was the one bigger than the band. She found solo success with guest spots on '03 Bonnie and Clyde' and 'The Closer I Get To You', before releasing 2003's Dangerously In Love, a storming chart success. With roles in Dreamgirls, Austin Powers in Goldmember and The Fighting Temptations she stayed in the spotlight while Destony's Child disbanded. At the close of 2008 she released I Am... Sasha Fierce, an album that would spawn eight singles internationally, some of which proved to be the best-selling and most popular of her career - most of her current top ten are from the album, proving that you've yet to get bored of it. The album's success, her talents as a singer, and her open support of Barack Obama while campaigning for the Democratic party nomination resulted in Knowles performing 'America The Beautiful' at his inauguration ceremony in January. The lengthy I Am... tour will continue next year, with shows planned into next summer.

artist.name: Animal Collective
artist.blurb: While pop rules the Best of 2009 pretty unashamedly, the success of Animal Collective proves that a wider audience has developed a taste for some of the stranger side of the genre in the last few years. Alongside fellow Best Of... act Grizzly Bear the four-piece collective have brought experimental pop and freak folk to the airwaves, becoming one of the most frequently referenced bands of 2009 on classic album polls and indie charts. Scrobbles of the band's back catalogue had always been consistent but modest, however Merriweather Post Pavilion opened them up to a huge number of new listeners. The drop off of listeners proved much slower than many of their fellow top twenty acts, as 'My Girls' became a surprise radio hit and 'Summertime Clothes' became one of the summer's indie anthems, helped along by mainstream tastemakers like David Letterman. They embarked on a huge live tour, stopping off throughout North America and Europe and at favoured festivals to more than 33,000 of you, unleashing unexpected dance classic 'Brother Sport' on an audience prepared for shoegaze. Animal Collective will be taking a break from touring when their current dates wrap up, however collective member Panda Bear has announced a short tour in January.

artist.name: Green Day
artist.blurb: It's been fifteen years since Green Day erupted onto MTV with 'Basket Case'. Hailing from California, the three bratty boys began spouting what would become the cliches that continue to define pop-punk to this day. After six albums the band took a four year break and, after a sly side project, came back with American Idiot, an album that sought to define opposition to globalisation and its macabre figurehead George W. Bush. Even after five years, songs like 'Boulevard of Broken Dreams' and 'American Idiot' top the band's chart, although the release of 21st Century Breakdown mixed things up a little. After putting another side project to bed, the band's eighth studio album proved to be a three act concept narrative, loosely telling the story of Gloria and Christian and their troubled romance in the faltering hours following the Bush Administration. Lead single 'Know Your Enemy' stomped around the radio all summer, angry and bitter, trailing the new album and its seven million scrobbles wonderfully. It was soon followed by '21 Guns', 'East Jesus Nowhere' and the title track as you lapped up the new record. The band will continue to tour in support of 21st Century Breakdown through 2010.

artist.name: Yeah Yeah Yeahs
artist.blurb: Now one of the defining bands of the decade, many assumed that Brooklyn's Yeah Yeah Yeahs would melt away after their 2003 debut Fever To Tell, like so many young art-rock sensations had done before them. It took three years of writing, recording and touring but follow up Show Your Bones proved that wrong; band members Nick Zinner, Brian Chase and Karen O stepped up, cementing their position as an all-powerful touring band with the release of Tell Me What Rockers To Swallow and teasing fans with new work on the IsIs EP. They returned in 2009 with It's Blitz!, an album that surprised fans and listeners with its surprisingly upbeat tone, light melodies and a slew of indie-club floor-fillers. 'Heads will Roll' and 'Zero' shot up the band's chart, while 'Skeletons' and 'Little Shadow' provided the emotional tug at the heart the band perfected with 'Maps'. As the band played the summer festivals their plays reached a new peak, while Karen O's soundtrack for Where The Wild Things Are began to start generating attention as well as your scrobbles. The band will be touring Japan and Mexico in the new year, and will be announcing more plans for 2010 soon.

artist.name: Kanye West
artist.blurb: It might have been impossible to escape Kanye West's face this year, as his MTV Awards interruption became one of the year's fastest spreading memes. West popped up all over the internet to steal the limelight and make hamfisted apologies, while even U.S. President Barack Obama branded him a jackass. Released in November 2008, 808s and Heartbreak is the rapper's fourth studio album since his 2004 debut The College Dropout. Reportedly recorded in just three weeks, the album marked a huge departure for West as he layered the tracks with auto-tuned vocals and stuttering drum machines. Critics weren't sure what to think at first, but Last.fm listeners responded with repeat plays and loved tracks, pushing old favourite 'Jesus Walks' out of his top five tracks with new cuts 'Heartless' and 'Love Lockdown'. Despite cancelling the 'Fame Kills' tour West has been around the world, attracting over 13,000 of you to gigs and festivals in the last twelve months. With an appearance in Family Guy spin-off The Cleveland Show in the works — Yo, Kanye, I'm really happy you made the top ten, and I'mma let you finish, but we just gotta check out the next artist, who had one of the top nine tracks of the year.

artist.name: Britney Spears
artist.blurb: One of the most powerful women in pop, Britney Spears launched her comeback campaign late in 2008 with the release of Circus, continuing the trail with covershoots, hit singles and the all-conquering world tour. The Mississippi native played 97 dates to almost one million people, and took more than $83,000,000 at the box office. The huge appetite for her glossy-pop appears tough to satiate: listeners have played tracks from Circus more than six million times. Not bad for someone the tabloid press came close to writing off at the start of 2008. Spears cast personal problems aside to record Circus, her sixth studio album. 'Womanizer' was the first single, released in Autumn 2008, and you went crazy for it, swiftly followed by the naughtily titled 'If U Seek Amy'. Despite that, she has vied for the top spot of 'Most Unwanted' with Katy Perry, Rihanna and Lady GaGa over the last twelve months. Does the phrase 'Guilty Pleasure' mean anything to any of you? The Singles Collection was released in November, wrapping up a very successful year for the starlet. Spears currently has no tour plans announced for 2010, but expect to see her on the gossip pages soon.

artist.name: Fall Out Boy
artist.blurb: Originally scattered through Illinois, Fall Out Boy formed in the early days of 2001, eventually releasing a mini-album in 2003 titled Evening Out With Your Girlfriend, a title worthy of what would become their trademark sense of humour. They broke onto MTV with From Under The Cork Tree, which spawned hit singles 'Sugar, We're Going Down' and 'Dance, Dance', and the four-piece has since become a radio fixture and a highly-billed act at music festivals around the world. Following the flop viral campaign Fall Out Boy's Pete Wentz initiated last year (Citizens For Our Betterment) Folie à Deux was released in December 2008, featuring appearances by Pharrell, Panic! at the Disco and Debbie Harry. It was a critical success, and landed the band a slot on blink-182's reunion tour line-up as well as several hundred thousand scrobbles. Track 'What a Catch, Donnie' featured an epic array of collaborators, including Elvis Costello, and boasted a suitably epic promo to accompany it. Listening has tapered off over the last tweleve months, but you've returned to the band's back catalogue in the weeks following the release of 'Believers Never Die', a greatest hits collection that will doubtless see the band touring in 2010.

artist.name: Taylor Swift
artist.blurb: Formerly a MySpace sensation, Taylor Swift has been making music for years, distributing demos throughout her teens and waiting for the right conditions to record her brand of country. An accomplished songwriter, she has balanced the genre's ticks and limitations with a pop sensibility. Her music has a high-gloss charm that avoids the aggressively sexual pop of her rivals for a sweeter, more heartfelt approach to life and love. Her debut Taylor Swift proved a hit on the country charts, MTV and radio stations throughout the U.S. A record you've been listening to for much of the last year - and one of the oldest eligible albums in the chart - Swift's sophomore album Fearless was released in November 2008 and became an international success. It won over new fans quickly enough to become the thirteenth-hottest artist of the year at Last.fm, long before the VMA incident. That brought Swift and Kanye West to the attentiopn of the world's press not for winning an award (hymn to high-school crushes 'You Belong with Me' had won Best Video at the MTV bash) but for the interruption. On the plus side, her scrobbles rose, and Swift has remained popular since. Swift will be embarking on an extensive tour of North America in 2010, continuing until the summer.

artist.name: Muse
artist.blurb: In a sleepy village in English county Devon, a band came together that would later take over the world. Muse remain one of the startling successes of British Pop music; a three-piece that once appeared to be little more than Radiohead-aping miserablists have since evolved into glam-evoking prog-rock stadium legends. 1999 album Showbiz seemed to be relatively standard rock, a foray by a band on the fringes of the nu-metal explosion, but in 2003 they released epic space-opera Absolution and took their incredible live show around the world for the following two years, following it up with Black Holes & Revelations in 2006. Hotly anticipated, The Resistance was released in September and is the band's fifth studio album. In that short time it has generated five and a half million scrobbles, beating albums in the Top Forty that you've been listening to for a year. Prior to its release you'd been scrobbling the band's back catalog heavily, but tracks old ('Supermassive Black Hole', 'Time Is Running Out') and new ('Uprising', 'Undisclosed Desires') shot up afterwards and remain high. Muse have been relentlessly touring in 2009, and have dates booked as far away as September 2010. Expect to hear them for the next twelve months too.

artist.name: Black Eyed Peas
artist.blurb: Hailing from Los Angeles, Black Eyed Peas have been around for a little over a decade. They seem to have been a band with two sounds; their debut and sophomore albums (Behind the Front and Bridging The Gap) were backpack rap classics, at once combative and urgent. In 2003 the group were joined by Fergie, made an abrupt dash towards the firing lines of pop music with 'Where is The Love?', and became a worldwide smash hit. Apparently overnight, Black Eyed Peas were transformed into MTV stallwarts. The E.N.D. dropped in June, and promoting the album became a chance for founder Pea and producer will.i.am to talk about his vision of music for the future: "I'm trying to break away from the concept of an album. What is an album when you put 12 songs on iTunes and people can pick at it like scabs? That's not an album. There is no album anymore." Despite that, his band's album — a heavyweight 15 tracks in length — proved a popular relic of how music used to be, with almost a million of you trying tracks like 'I Gotta Feeling' and 'Boom Boom Pow'. The band will continue promoting The E.N.D. in 2010.

artist.name: Phoenix
artist.blurb: The hottest band in continental Europe — in fact, the most popular artist in the Best of 2009 that doesn't hail from North America or the U.K. — French indie rockers Phoenix have been releasing consistently charming and infectious indie-pop since 2000's United. Hailing from Versailles, and spawned from the same culture that brought the world Daft Punk and Air, the band bring precise, playful electronics to a world dominated by serious men in skinny jeans. With a much-adoring fanbase and boosted by the release of Wolfgang Amadeus Phoenix, this year the four piece are on the cusp of stardom. The band's fourth album was previewed with '1901', a jerky single sharing a bit in common with Modest Mouse and Clap Your Hands Say Yeah. First single proper, 'Lisztomania', followed soon after: in an interview earlier this year the band confessed that the YouTube fan-video of the track — featuring clips from The Breakfast Club, Pretty In Pink, Footlose and more — might well be the band's "best video", despite the official big-budget offering shot at Bayreuth Festspielhaus. It's a sign of just how dedicated their audience are. Phoenix closed 2009 with a North American Tour, and will make a live return in the new year.

artist.name: Paramore
artist.blurb: To the half-a-million of you who played Paramore's latest album, this band needs no introduction. To those of you left, the Tennesse five piece have become a global rock phenomenon, a direct line to the bedrooms and headphones of teenagers everywhere. The band are fronted by Hayley Williams, a new pin-up for a generation of guys and girls who are just as happy in a mosh pit as in a bedroom reading books by Stephanie Meyer. In fact, it's almost impossible to mention Paramore without mentioning Twilight. Part of the band's reach is down to the film franchise, for which they've appeared prominently on both soundtracks. Tie-in videos and touring followed, and like it or not they've become the musical outlet for the saga's fans. None of which gets in the way of some incredible pop-rock; over three albums Paramore have honed their heavy ballads, winning over an initially disdainful Kerrang! and courting the respect of established bands like New Found Glory and Jimmy Eat World. They played well over 100 headline shows in 2009, and will begin another heavy year on the road in Japan in support of their latest album Brand New Eyes.

artist.name: Kelly Clarkson
artist.blurb: Hard to believe that it's been seven years since Kelly Clarkson won the first series of American Idol in 2002. Following the troubled release of My December - which resulted in the Texas-born singer parting ways with her label and her management - Clarkson produced a relatively jagged record, falling back on synths and drum machines rather than the rockier sound with which she had found success. From that came All I Ever Wanted, a surprisingly danceable record that made the most of her natural vocal talents by playing them off against auto-tuned and programmed cuts. Opening single 'My Life Would Suck Without You' made history by leaping 96 places in the Billboard 100 on its January release. It was a perfect trail for the album to come. Back with a dance beat and boasting a super-charged chorus it sounded like a celebration for the singer after the darker My December. It was soon followed by 'I Do Not Hook Up', a song originally recorded by Katy Perry for her unreleased album (A) Katy Perry, and it returned to her pop-rock roots before third single 'Already Gone' brought a down-tempo pace to her radio releases. In the new year Clarkson will be touring Europe and Australia. She is likely to start work on her next album by the end of 2010.

artist.name: Placebo
artist.blurb: When Placebo formed in 1994 they probably never expected to be the chart bothering heroes of Brit-rock they are now. The London-based band are a perennial favourite in festival line-ups, and have stretched way beyond their initial black-clad, eyeliner-smeared alternative fanbase. They've touched Last.fm listeners with their blend of Nirvana's lyricism and Depeche Mode's dark synth sound, and are part of a wave of bands that includes Muse and Incubus. Placebo's latest effort Battle for the Sun had a pop-appeal that resulted a number one album throughout Europe and an MTV award. Battle For The Sun didn't spawn the hit single they previously achieved with 'Every You Every Me' and 'The Bitter End', but it did result in a few listener favourites. The title track has all the erratic stomp and thrust of a live belter, while 'For What It's Worth' sported a surprise chant-along chorus that resounded through the festival circuit. They 130 of them this year alone, reaching just shy of 50,000 of you in total. As you've guessed, Placebo are a ridiculously hard-working live act. 2010 will see them on the road until at least March, and it's a fair bet that they'll make a few more appearances with the return of the sun.

artist.name: La Roux
artist.blurb: Kicking off our top 20 are London-based synth-pop duo La Roux. They stormed the UK in 2009, with singles 'Quicksand' and 'In For The Kill' getting heavy rotation throughout the summer. Frontwoman Elly Jackson became an ice-queen pin-up and has been touted as the inheritor to Annie Lennox's cold crown, embracing androgynous pop while appearing on billboards and posters throughout Europe. La Roux's career started with under the radar remixes and releases on Kitsune before the debut dropped in June. Touted by music bloggers and journos on web and print, many were waiting for the pair to flop, but storming single 'Bulletproof' proved them wrong and paved the way for a summer of attention on the festival cicuit. Singles and remixes have kept you coming back, with new edits and cuts being scrobbled over the year. Often mentioned in the same breath as Little Boots and Florence + the Machine, La Roux beat both in the heart and charts of Last.fm listeners, with over 4 ¼ million plays in the last twelve months. Touring heavily in 2009, you saw them play at festivals alongside Fever Ray and Metric, rounding out a summer of electropop. La Roux will be on tour long into 2010, starting in North America in January before playing throughout Europe.

artist.name: Grizzly Bear
artist.blurb: Just missing out on a Top Twenty place are Grizzly Bear, a freak-folk outfit hailing from New York. Having started out as the solo project of vocalist Edward Droste, the band came together through 2004/5, eventually settling into the four-piece it currently consists of. Grizzly Bear released their third album — Veckatimest — to widespread acclaim as well as surprising commercial success; a sign that, in 2009, a huge number of listeners were happy to tackle apparently difficult work by relatively unknown bands. They recently broke into BBC Radio 1's Playlist with their track 'Two Weeks', resulting in daytime radio exposure for a band once associated with limited vinyl releases. While the album's scrobbles peaked dramatically on release in May (having been widely played after an unmastered version leaked earlier in the year) the number of listeners has been building steadily. Rather than being a slow burn record, summer festivals and extensive touring have put Grizzly Bear in a new field, helping them find new audiences. Warp Records, known for their electronica output, have taken special care of the group, and more than 30,000 of you saw them at live shows throughout this year. They will tour Europe in 2010 after a brief visit to Australia.

artist.name: Arctic Monkeys
artist.blurb: Arctic Monkeys, four young men hailing from Sheffield, have been causing a stir in the UK since the release of 'I Bet You Look Good On The Dancefloor' in 2005; a snarling single aimed at the poised scenesters and hipsters populating clubs in London, New York and Brighton. Initial comparisons to The Libertines proved both unpopular and unfair among listeners, as Alex Turner began to demonstrate a lyrical dexterity more befitting John Cooper Clarke than their apparent southern equivalent. Before long the band were hyped stateside, picking up best newcomer plaudits and playing several sold out tours. In 2009 the band released Humbug, their third full-length album, which they recorded with Josh Homme. You've played tracks from Humbug more then four and a half million times since it came out in August, falling especially hard for lead single 'Crying Lightning'. Sporting a surprisingly high-tech video, the track saw the band adopt a sound filled with space and echos, exactly the kind of production the man responsible for The Desert Sessions excels at. Since release they've been touring pretty solidly, and will continue this through Europe into 2010. Turner's side project The Last Shadow Puppets appeared in Last.fm's Best of 2008, making him the only artist to appear two years running. Shame you didn't make the Top 20 this time though, hey Alex?

artist.name: A Day to Remember
artist.blurb: One of the hardest touring bands in the Best of 2009, A Day To Remember are a post-hardcore five-piece hailing from Ocala, Florida. In 2009 they played 276 sets, 80 of them at festivals, to more than 22,500 of you, in support of their latest album Homesick. It was a cover of Kelly Clarkson's 'Since U Been Gone' that grabbed attention in 2007, later re-released alongside their second album For Those Who Have Heart. Homesick wasn't a great experimental leap for A Day To Remember, but listeners lapped up tracks like 'The Downfall of Us All' and 'If It Means A Lot To You'. Videos, littering YouTube, show audiences throwing themselves around before the band, who have learned to play a tight and furious live set in their five years of touring. 'If It Means A Lot To You' in particular hit a heartwarming note over the festival season, with a softer take from vocalist Jeremy McKinnon blended with Sierra Kusterbeck's guest vocals. Homesick was re-released in October and acoustic versions of tracks 'Homesick' and 'Another Song About The Weekend' have caught your attention. In 2010 A Day To Remember will embark on tours of Australia, Japan and the UK before returning to North America.

artist.name: Röyksopp
artist.blurb: Electronic duo Röyksopp hail from Bergen, Norway, and are the standard bearers of Scandinavian music. The band have singles spanning a ten year career, including 'Eple'; a track not so much known as a chart topper, but as a bed for radio spots, adverts, soundtracks and montages throughout the six years since it's release. 'Eple' sees the band loop some of the lightest electronica through a three minute run time, nudging past Kraftwerk's vision of the future and replacing it with something altogether more cheerful. Taken from the band's best-known album Melody A.M., it remains their signature track. The juvenile, poppy nature of 'Eple' can be found throughout their 2009 offering Junior, an album which saw contributions from Robyn, Lykke Li and fellow Best of 2009 artist Karin Dreijer Andersson, a.k.a. Fever Ray. Lead single and opening track 'Happy Up Here' met with critical success and quickly stamped it's presence at the top of Röyksopp's most played chart. It was followed by the sublime 'The Girl and The Robot', featuring an earnest contribution from Robyn in which she laments a lover sharing more in common with a robot than a human. The duo plan to follow up Junior with Senior in 2010.

artist.name: Passion Pit
artist.blurb: Cambridge, Massachusetts five-piece Passion Pit came hot on the tail of last year's most popular debut act MGMT. With a quick line in danceable electronica, the band's Chunk of Change EP lit a fire in New York's club scene, despite its humble beginnings as an anniversary gift for singer Michael Angelakos' then-girlfriend. From the ashes of 'Sleepyhead' rose as a crowd-pleasing favourite, resulting in widespread exposure for the band on tastemaker blogs and 'Will be big in 2009...' charts. Now based in Boston, the band have moved on from this haphazard start, following the EP with album Manners, one of the most popular debuts on Last.fm this year. Manners opened with the stellar 'Make Light', a rising, stomping track making the most of their clockwork rhythm section and Angelakos' wild and spindly vocals. 'Little Secrets' followed, a surprise airplay favourite for the band, while 'The Reeling' brought the band a sound sometimes compared to 'Star Guitar' — era Chemical Brothers. By the end of the album, 'Sleephyhead' made another appearance, augmented with chimes and bells, securing its place among the most loved tracks of 2009. The band will start 2010 on tour, taking in Australia, Europe and North America.

artist.name: Bat for Lashes
artist.blurb: Natasha Khan's performances as Bat For Lashes have captivated audiences since debut release Fur and Gold in 2006. With a theatrical live set and an artistic direction favourably compared to Kate Bush and fellow Best of 2009 artist Fever Ray, the British-born singer has revelled in frivolous outfits and striking make-up, and has been welcomed into artistic hotbeds, Brooklyn and Brighton, with open arms. For fans she has been a consistently surprising artist, often openly revealing a blend of the playful and spiritual: her exclusive interview with Last.fm at San Fancisco's Outlands Festival revealed a pet obsession with Steven Spielberg, as well as a firm belief in the healing power of music. Two Suns, Bat For Lashes' second album, was released in April. In it Khan charts the journey of Pearl, an alter-ego she adopted while living in New York, a vapid, femme-fatale counterpoint to her own considered, holistic self. Single 'Daniel' was a crossover hit, spun on daytime radio, clubnights and TV spots, particularly in her native UK. Bat For Lashes' touring band had a heavy schedule throughout 2009, playing 93 shows and 17 festivals to an army of Last.fm listeners. Her touring band currently features Ben Christophers, New Young Pony Club's Sarah Jones and former Ash guitarist Charlotte Hatherley, and they are set to join Coldplay in their South American tour in February.

artist.name: The All-American Rejects
artist.blurb: Pop-rock group The All-American Rejects released their debut album in 2002, and broke into International airplay lists with 'Swing, Swing', a ridiculously infectious track you've played over 800,000 times. Featuring an organ leading into a stumbling guitar riff, the track explodes with a drum crash before singer Tyson Ritter emotes a surprisingly cheerful song about heartbreak and moving on. The single led to the band's inclusion on soundtracks to The O.C., Smallville and American Wedding, as well as numerous sell-out headline tours for the Oklahoma four-piece. When The World Comes Down was released just before Christmas 2008, and you stayed loyal to the record over the year. Lead single 'Gives You Hell' has become a firm favourite; with its sing-a-long chorus attacking a disloyal ex and three versions of the accompanying promo video (in which the band instigate a colourful lawn war between suburban neighbours). Opening track 'I Wanna' also rides high in the band's chart, with looped synths giving the band a slightly darker musical tone. The releases scored the band a support slot on Blink-182's Reunion Tour, one of the most successful shows of the year. The band appear on the Band Hero playlist and will reportedly begin recording new material in 2010.

artist.name: Nickelback
artist.blurb: An International success story, despite widespread critical panning, Nickelback returned at the close of 2008 with Dark Horse, an album which saw the Canadian rockers do, well, exactly what they usually do: produce a slick pop-rock record filled with the kind of anthems that slip effortlessly into radio playlists. The record spawned no less than seven single releases, and it is a testament to (songwriter and lead vocalist) Chad Kroger's pop sensibility that so many stand-alone tracks could be culled from one offering. Of course, Nickelback shot to fame in 2001 with the unexpected smash hit 'How You Remind Me', a track that still gets thousands of plays a week from Last.fm listeners. It is perhaps that song's ubiquity which continues to raise hackles among music journalists and reviewers, although many admit that the band have become "bulletproof"; their music is so perfectly pitched at a wider audience that commercial success is an inevitability. Given that the group continue to play sell-out stadium tours, and release hit record upon hit record, that's perhaps a fair assumption. The band signed a deal with LiveNation last summer, covering three albums and World tours. Expect to hear more from them in 2010.

artist.name: Guns N' Roses
artist.blurb: Another legendary band born of the 1980s, Guns N' Roses were formed in 1985 by Axl Rose, and has featured a little over 20 members since its original four-piece line-up. Just as the polls closed on last year's Last.fm 'Best Of 2008' the group released their sixth studio album — Chinese Democracy — and at the the start of the year it was all anyone could talk about. Without question, one of the most eagerly anticipated albums of the last decade, Chinese Democracy had attained something of a legendary status after languishing for more than ten years in production hell. It was rumoured to be an experimental epic, a concept album, perhaps even a multi-disc release to rival the band's original plans for Use Your Illusion, and that legend became something Last.fm listeners found infectious; it is the only album outside of our Top Ten listened to by more than 1 million of you. Nevertheless, it is their super-charged back catalogue that sits atop their charts: 'Knockin' on Heaven's Door', 'November Rain', 'Paradise City', 'Sweet Child O' Mine', 'Welcome To The Jungle'... it's a group of songs found in the dictionary under the definition of Rock.

artist.name: U2
artist.blurb: Scrobbles for U2 and Depeche Mode were incredibly close, but the Irish rockers just pipped the electro-pop godfathers to a place in the Top 30 of 2009. This year they released No Line on the Horizon, an epic affair that saw the band enlist Brian Eno — producer of last year's chart-dominating Viva la Vida — in the songwriting process. They accompanied the release with Linear, an experimental film shot by Anton Corbijn, designed to provide listeners with an immersive visual experience. Perhaps unsurprisingly though, it is also U2's back catalogue that dominate their charts, and it's a collection of tracks that bear repeat listenings. 'With Or Without You' manages to soothe lovers and the heartbroken equally well with its powerful chorus and Bono's soaring performance, while young listeners might be surprised at the grit and anger of 'Sunday Bloody Sunday', 'Pride (In The Name of Love)' is the closest Ireland has come to a Springsteen figurehead, and relatively new classic 'Beautiful Day' is a an explosive pop track found on trailers and TV spots on almost every station in every continent. U2 haven't slowed down in 30 years, and continue their 360º Tour well into Summer 2010.

artist.name: Depeche Mode
artist.blurb: Depeche Mode, a band with almost 60 million total scrobbles to date, who share at least some of the responsibility for the swathe of electro-pop artists in the last decade, probably need little introduction to Last.fm listeners. 'Enjoy The Silence', 'Personal Jesus' and 'World In My Eyes' all sprang from Violator, the group's seventh studio album, and led to them becoming one of the most popular (and influential) acts of the '80s. Hailing from Essex, on the East coast of England, they now live scattered throughout the World, rich on their efforts... and yet they're not even in the Top 30 of 2009. You lot are hard to impress. Their twelfth release, Sounds of the Universe, came out in April. More than 3/4 million of you have played it so far, and singles 'Wrong' and 'Peace' have become entrenched in the band's top tracks scrobbled this year. Album plays peaked as the Tour of the Universe began to rumble on, despite being beset by delays and rescheduled shows due to health problems and vocal rest for singer Dave Gahan. The Tour of The Universe continues into 2010, and the band's relentless schedule of festival and stadium performances shows little sign of slowing down.

artist.name: Fever Ray
artist.blurb: Better known as one half of The Knife, Karin Dreijer Andersson recorded Fever Ray in 2008 while the brother-sister electronic duo were on hiatus. The Swedish musician released an atmospheric classic; laced with darkness and abstract lyricism, there's a dream-like element to the album which live sets and promo videos have played up, while the monochrome sleeve art became a digital-woodcut, stamping the record into shop windows and scrobble charts. Trying to pin down Andersson's thoughts on the project seems to be close to impossible. While she strayed a little closer to the music press than The Knife, she kept a lot to herself while promoting Fever Ray, content to let the listeners interpret the meanings and merits of the tracks. What is clear is that many of you seem to be listening to Fever Ray as an album; many tracks have scrobbled similarly, no one 'single' leaping away from the pack. For an artist concerned with the fidelity of the listening experience that's probably how Andersson would want it. The final Fever Ray show has already been announced, while The Knife are due to release a recording of their composition for electro-opera Tomorrow, In A Year in 2010.

artist.name: Eminem
artist.blurb: Marshall Mathers (a.k.a. Slim Shady, a.k.a. Eminem) has been an almost permanent fixture on the musical landscape since the release of the Slim Shady LP in 1999. Always close to Dr. Dre and often backed up by D12, the 37 year old has courted controversy at every possible turn, while also releasing some of the most popular records (think 'Without Me', 'Sing For The Moment', and 'Lose Yourself' for starters) of the decade. This year the Detroit rapper dropped Relapse, the first in a series of planned returns for Mathers after a few years babysitting production at Shady Records. Laced with the trademark skits and half-stories fans have come to know Eminem for, Relapse wasn't the instant critical success his previous albums have been: Mathers made a big deal of killing his Slim Shady persona with the release of Encore and Curtain Call, and many expected Eminem to spend longer out of the spotlight. Despite that, you've pushed tracks like 'Bagpipes from Baghdad', 'Insane' and 'Beautiful' into his most played, while lead single 'We Made You' is currently his most popular of the year, once again provoking comment from all sides (Feminists, Celebrities, Right-Wing pundits, Left-wing pundits and others all had something to say). Relapse 2 is due in 2010.

artist.name: The xx
artist.blurb: Three-piece The xx hail from South London, England, graduates of the same school that brought the World Hot Chip, Four Tet and Burial. There must be something in the water: dark soundscapes, hollow spaces, and bleak whistles and beeps are common to the four groups but, in The xx, the music comes with whispered vocals and dream pop flourishes. Despite that, The xx are incredibly hard to pin down. Listener favourite 'Crystalised' gently wails through the speakers with a bounce and pace that got it repeat plays and a slew of loves. But it won't set a dancefloor alight. 'Infinity' comes close to being a ballad, but the group's lazy vocals and slow-funk bass are matched with handclaps, finger clicks and (what sound like) bongos. Every time they come close to a pop song they vault away with impossible speed. Their remix of Florence + The Machine's 'You've Got The Love' has gotten a lot of love from you since it's November release, and they won new fans supporting the theatrical singer in the Autumn, despite losing a band member to exhaustion. They'll be another of the bands enjoying Australia's summer sun on the Big Day Out Tour, before more European shows in 2010.

artist.name: Metric
artist.blurb: Formed ten years ago in the confines of a loft space in Williamsburg, Metric have been on the cusp of shattering pop charts since the release of Live It Out in 2005. Occasional members of Toronto's Broken Social Scene and flatmates of Brooklyn legends TV on the Radio and Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Metric have won over more than just friends in the Indie community and their rabid fanbase lapped up this year's Fantasies. Songwriter Emily Haines admitted that much of the album material came from an escape to Buenos Aires, where she tried to shrug off the pressure to stay cool, bestowed on her by the music press and bloggers. It seems to have worked. Your scrobbles came in quickly, but Fantasies peaked with the release of 'Sick Muse' in June. You started to turn back to singles 'Help I'm Alive' and 'Gimme Sympathy', unexpectedly finding alternative anthems to better 'Combat Baby', 'Dead Disco' and the crossover hit 'Monster Hospital'. A European tour and an intense festival circuit soon followed, where some 24,000 of you turned out in all elements to see Haines lead the group's indie-pop dance-alongs. Closing the year with Festive shows in North America, the band will reportedly appear on the Scott Pilgrim vs. The World soundtrack in 2010.

artist.name: The Fray
artist.blurb: Continuing in the fine tradition of college rock bands across North America, The Fray are the latest four-piece to step into the spotlight after becoming small-town heroes. Hailing from Denver, Colorado, the four-piece originally came into prominence with single 'How To Save a Life', the title track from their debut album, which appeared in TV spots and soundtracks for Ghost Whisperer, Cold Case and Grey's Anatomy and spent 58 consecutive weeks in the Billboard Charts. The band released their second full-length record back in February, an eponymous effort that saw them embrace the same warm piano and comforting vocals of the first album. It was a winning formula, bolstered by a string section and subtle performances from The Fray's dual vocalists Isaac Slade and Joe King. You quickly warmed to 'You Found Me' and 'Never Say Never', which have jockeyed for position in the band's chart since release. The Fray have yet to announce plans for 2010 but, given the success of the last three years, it's unlikely to be a quiet one.

artist.name: Regina Spektor
artist.blurb: Moscow born Regina Spektor began her career as a musician in the Lower East Side of New York; gigging at anti-folk and taste-maker venues the Knitting Factory, The Sidewalk Cafe and the Cake Shop, while self-releasing her first two albums 11:11 and Songs. Her major label debut, 2004's Soviet Kitsch, landed her International attention and, while she hasn't quite reached celebrity status, she has become one of the most respected singer songwriters of her generation. You responded in your thousands to Far, Spektor's fifth album. Tracks 'Eet' and 'The Calculation' both sneaked into her top ten most-scrobbled chart, and 'Laughing With' even managed to climb higher than 'Us', one of the tracks from Soviet Kitsch that secured her success. Though she seldom strays far from her piano, Spektor's music remains fresh and challenging, and her attention to orchestration always brings out something new in her tracks. Vocal gymnastics are an excellent description of her live sets, which manage to whisper and scream within moments. Spektor will spend December closing a tour that has taken in most of the World, and captivated over 12,000 of you. No announcements yet regarding her plans for 2010, but she's likely to be taking her piano back on the road again.

artist.name: Kasabian
artist.blurb: Since their debut album's release in September 2004, British band Kasabian have been stomping around the UK charts. Five years on and breakout single 'Club Foot' remains a Last.fm listener favourite, and their dubby, dance-influenced spin on guitar rock often results in comparisons to Primal Scream, Oasis and The Stone Roses. Produced by Dan The Automator, the mastermind behind Gorillaz debut album, West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum debuted at number one in the UK charts shortly after it's June release. The album — the band's third — saw them adopt a heavy sound, leaving a lot of space for trippy flourishes. Songwriter Sergio Pizzorno revealed to the press that the album "isn't about the place, I just first heard about it on a TV documentary, and the words just struck me." Last.fm listeners responded well to the albums release, as well as teaser singles 'Fire' and 'Vlad the Impaler', but it was a couple of weeks after release, around the time of the band's Glastonbury performance, that the album's popularity peaked. After a long Summer of touring and a heavy presence on the festival circuit, Kasabian will start 2010 playing Australia's Big Day Out Tour. They will then return to Europe to for shows in February.

artist.name: Florence + The Machine
artist.blurb: British singer Florence Welsh started making a mark in early 2008, her London shows carving out a place for a theatric stage set-up and glam outfits long before her music became a fixture on TV soundtracks and idents. Her revolving backing group became known as 'The Machine' after an in-joke with longtime keyboard player Isabella Summers, resulting in the most improbably name-buzz band of 2009. Bursting out with a thump and slap, 'Kiss with a Fist' wound up being a rockier effort than her album proved. Second single 'Dog Days are Over' got Florence + The Machine enough coverage to make 'Hot in 2009' lists and, after being touted on music blogs, the track made waves on Last.fm charts. Lungs was released in July in Europe, alongside a slew of live dates and festival performances, but it was a b-side that started to get the most attention: 'Dog Days...' had featured a cover of Candi Staton's power ballad 'You've Got The Love', and it became one of your favourites within weeks. Florence + The Machine close the year with a single release of 'You've Got The Love', and will start 2010 in Australia before a European tour in February.

artist.name: Little Boots
artist.blurb: Little Boots hails from the North West England, and has been one of the overnight successes in British Pop in 2009. Picking up a cult following with her Tenori-On covers (Kate Bush's 'Running Up That Hill', Blur's 'To The End', and 'Day and Nite' by Kid Cudi all got the bedroom treatment), she soon found herself booked on UK tastemaker Jools Holland's Later... show and in the pages of Rolling Stone as 'one to watch'. As she quickly moved from lo-fi bedroom clips to big-budget, glossy pop-gloss videos, Little Boots' fans adjusted well: 'New In Town' — which featured on the Jennifer's Body soundtrack — 'Remedy' and 'Earthquake' all got high scrobble counts as their videos went live. Recently 'Stuck on Repeat' has shot to the top of the chart, after featuring in trailers for the latest series of Heroes, among others, while the track's Fake Blood Remix also crept into her Top Ten. Little Boots spent much of 2009 on tour and more than 30,000 of you turned out to see her. Playing Summer festivals back-to-back, she will close the year on a solo tour before returning with new material next year.
